Telling a story from data

Fabrice Mettler

2025-05-05

About the dataset

The data set airquality contains measurements of the air quality in New York from May 1, 1973 to September 30, 1973. The data frame contains 153 observations on 6 numeric variables including the mean ozone (ppb) from 1300 to 1500 hours at Roosevelt Island, solar radiation in Langleys in the frequency band 4000-7700 Angstroms from 0800 to 1200 hours at Central Park, average wind speed (miles/h) at 0700 and 1000 hours at LaGuardia Airport, the maximal temperature (degrees F) at LaGuardia Airport, the month of the year and the day of the month.

colSums(is.na(airquality)) # checking if there are NAs in the data set
##   Ozone Solar.R    Wind    Temp   Month     Day 
##      37       7       0       0       0       0
airquality_clean <- airquality |> # removing NAs
  drop_na()

airquality_clean <- airquality_clean |> #  create a new column with the dates
  mutate(
    Dates = make_date(year = 1973, month = Month, day = Day))

airquality_clean$Month <- as.factor(airquality_clean$Month)

knitr::kable(head(airquality_clean)) # presenting an overview of the data set

Question to answer:

What is the temporal pattern of ozone over the analysed time (May - September)

Analysis

First, lets get an overview of the data by presenting the range and mean of measured ozone, temperature. For the further analysis, NAs were excluded.

summary_airquality <- airquality_clean |>
  summarise(
    mean_ozone = mean(Ozone),
    mean_radiation = mean(Solar.R),
    mean_temp = mean(Temp)
  )

knitr::kable(summary_airquality, caption = "Some Summaries of the data set")
Some Summaries of the data set
mean_ozone mean_radiation mean_temp
42.0991 184.8018 77.79279 
ggplot(airquality_clean, aes(x = Dates, y = Ozone)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +  # optional: connects the points in order
  labs(title = "Ozone by Day")

ggplot(
  data = airquality_clean,
  aes(x = Temp, y = Ozone, colour = Month)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(x = "Temperature (F)",
       y = "Ozone (ppb)") +
  scico::scale_color_scico_d(palette = "bilbao")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
